<TITLE> PM concerned over 'admission business' </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 2 (bdnews24.com)  Prime minister Sheikh Hasina has expressed grave concern over the practice of granting admission educational institutions including universities, by giving bribes. "It's a shame that some teachers are allegedly involved," press secretary Abul Kalam Azad told reporters quoting Hasina. She made the statement at a meeting with a 31-member delegation of the University Council Standing Committee, formed by the vice chancellors, at her office on Sunday. The prime minister is understood to have urged the delegation not to get involves or tolerate 'bhorti banijjo' (admission business). Azad said that the VCs shared the overall scenario with the prime minister. She stressed the need to establish universities in every district and said, "We want to ensure higher education to students from all districts." Hasina also urged the VCs to ensure congenial environment for scholastic pursuit in the universities. She reportedly told the delegation that it was not possible for the government to do this alone. bdn
